5000|$|Lex loci protectionis is {{generally}} accepted as the prevailing {{choice of law}} rule for IP rights, at least as concerns the existence, validity, scope and duration of the rights. Article 8 (1) of the European Union's Rome II Regulation codifies it as follows: The law applicable to <b>a</b> non-contractual <b>obligation</b> <b>arising</b> from <b>an</b> infringement of an intellectual property right shall be {{the law of the}} country for which protection is claimed.|$|R
