40|$|RADMET – Radionuclide {{metrology}} for standardization {{and policy}} support (51603) The biennial ICRM conference is providing {{an opportunity for}} the exchange of information on the development of techniques and new applications of radionuclide metrology, and to encourage international co-operation in this field. The last conference was held in September 2011 in Tsukuba, Japan. Objectives, policy relevance and content of workshop The conference will include oral and poster presentations, and additional meetings of the ICRM Working Groups will provide an informal setting for deepening discussions of the conference themes. A special session on science-based advice to policy makers will be a novelty at this conference; a speaker from DG ENER is invited. The conference topics Intercomparisons, Measurement standards and reference materials, Radionuclide metrology in life sciences and Quality assurance and uncertainty evaluation in radioactivity measurements – next to those on techniques – will be of special value for target countries, developing a measurement infrastructure in radioactivity. Within several of the conference topics, radioactivity measurement in environmental samples will be an important issue, close {{to the needs of the}} target countries with <b>a</b> view to <b>obligations</b> <b>arising</b> from the Euratom Treaty for member states. In particular, intercomparisons organised on behalf of DG ENER among environmental monitoring laboratories have always been discussed during the past four ICRM conferences. Date, place and duration Deadline for application Target deadline for results of selection Participants profil...|$|R
